steps.description:
This step requires constant supervision, as chocolate burns easily:
Stir the melting chocolate often. If you're melting it in a pan or double boiler, stir constantly on low heat until the chocolate is fully melted. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/49/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Check the melting chocolate every 30 seconds. If you're melting the chocolate in a microwave, set it to cook for 30 seconds. Check and stir before returning it to cook for another 30 seconds. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/ff/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove the melted chocolate from the heat source when it has a smooth, silky consistency. Now it's time to quickly create your cups. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":308,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":508.4065934065934,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Stir the mixture constantly to ensure complete integration. Also, stirring the chocolate will minimize the possibility the chocolate will burn. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/03/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/03/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove from the heat source while a few chocolate chunks are still visible. Combine with a bowl of whipping cream mixed with gelatin. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/80/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/80/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make sure a full 30 minutes has passed if you're unsure whether the chocolate is ready. Gently prick the top of the water balloon with a thin needle to release the air; do this carefully so the balloon doesn't explode. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9d/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9d/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Allow the balloon to deflate and line the bottom of your cup. Wait for all the air to be released before proceeding to the next step. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5a/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5a/Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-Hot-Chocolate-Cups-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
